@gpooley @_HannahRitchie Even in supposed "oil country" like Texas, solar and wind accounted for 28% of power generation in the state in 2021. Source: https://t.co/2cH5n71cxk

Renewables + storage are the present and future. Burning dino fuels are the past.

@gpooley @_HannahRitchie True energy independence or security comes from that local util mix playing on strengths of renewable potential in that area. For Seattle, we're water-rich so hydro makes up the bulk. https://t.co/2WsCp9uOdG In much of the US, wind + solar + batteries would rock.

@gpooley @_HannahRitchie Could easily do grid-tied solar on hospital facilities to save $$ + have battery backup for emergencies. Local utils could adjust their renewables portfolio + storage to keep power flowing as they already do.
@meamZ_MZ @gpooley @_HannahRitchie And the speed to deploy at least solar + battery, especially on a hyperlocal level, is unmatched by any other form of power generation, full stop.
RT @GBBranstetter: POV: You're the mother of an 11-year-old trans kid in Texas. One of your child's classmates caught COVID and now your ki…

@gpooley @_HannahRitchie As with many things, diversity of energy sources/portfolios matters and even some limited fossil fuels work well for some industries until battery tech can catch up there, too.
@gpooley @_HannahRitchie Safe, modern nuclear can be part of the solution but is incredibly difficult to deploy. Solar is quick/easy to install & battery storage is likewise.

@gpooley @_HannahRitchie Plus, the ultimate energy independence is having solar on your roof and a battery or two in your garage. Or solar farms in sunny/hot areas that can help shade/cool crops below. To me, that's beautiful.

@gpooley @_HannahRitchie Subsidies keep fossil fuel prices artificially low. "Ugly" is subjective. Oil derricks are ugly. Horrible air quality from burning fossil fuels is ugly.

Batteries are essentially infinitely recyclable and more jobs will be created by the innovative companies pioneering there.

@gpooley @_HannahRitchie Batteries. Large-scale storage in batteries (or other creative means like pumped water) will smooth out the supply. Have solar in Seattle since 2018 and no bill since. Solar/wind/storage works.
